	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>EU  IUU regulation: Fish import bans to be proposed against Guinea, Belize and Cambodia</h1>

			
			<h4>
												22 December 2013
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>The European Fisheries Commissioner announced at a press conference that, despite the European Commission working closely with Guinea, Belize and Cambodia to set up effective control measures, these countries “have not addressed structural problems and have failed to show real commitment to tackling the problem of illegal fishing”. The EC is therefore proposing that the EU Council of Ministers should endorse import bans on fish products from these countries, to tackle the commercial benefits from illegal, unreported and unregulated (IUU) fishing activities in these countries’ waters.</p><p>Fiji, Panama, Sri Lanka, Togo and Vanuatu had also received warnings from the EC last December, but “they have all made credible progress in close cooperation with the Commission”. They are developing new legislation, and improved their monitoring, control surveillance systems. As a result, dialogue with these countries has been extended until the end of February 2014 when their progress will be evaluated.</p><p>Once the Commission’s proposal for a trade ban has been adopted by the Council, fisheries products caught by vessels flying these countries’ flags will be banned from importing into the EU. EU vessels will also have to stop fishing in these waters. Other forms of cooperation, such as joint ventures or fisheries agreements with these countries, will no longer be possible.</p><p>A Belize press article confirmed that sanctions from the EU are taken because of the high seas fleet carrying a Belizean flag: “these vessels have nothing to do with true Belizean fishers or vessels”. Local authorities “sell the Belize flag as a flag of convenience to international fishing vessels”. The same issue was highlighted in the Cambodian press: “Cambodia exports little fish to Europe itself, but it does allow its flag to be flown by many vessels.”</p><p>The EC Commissioner also announced that it had pre-notified South Korea, Ghana and Curaçao, and concluded, “We continue to put pressure on the countries which are fuelling the supply chain of illegal fishing be it as a coastal state, flag state, or flag of convenience. West Africa was identified as a major source of illegal fishing and my intention is now [to] take the same thorough approach in the Pacific.”</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>EC Maritime Affairs, Commissioner Damanaki statement on IUU fishing, 26 November 2013</p><p>
<a href="http://europa.eu/rapid/press-release_SPEECH-13-982_en.htm?subweb=347&amp;lang=en" target="_self">http://europa.eu/rapid/press-release_SPEECH-13-982_en.htm?subweb=347&amp...</a></p><p><i>Food World News</i>, ‘European Union proposes ban on fish imports from Belize, Cambodia, and Guinea’, 27 November 2013</p><p>
<a href="http://www.foodworldnews.com/articles/4699/20131127/the-european-union-proposes-ban-on-fish-imports-from-belize-cambodia-and-guinea.htm" target="_self">http://www.foodworldnews.com/articles/4699/20131127/the-european-union-p...</a></p><p><i>FishUpdate.com</i>, ‘EU plans export crackdown on countries fishing illegally’, 27 November 2013</p><p>
<a href="http://www.fishupdate.com/news/fullstory.php/aid/20443/EU_plans_export_crackdown_on_countries_fishing_illegally.html" target="_self">http://www.fishupdate.com/news/fullstory.php/aid/20443/EU_plans_export_c...</a></p><p><i>7 Newsbelize.com</i>, ‘Belize blacklisted, gets a black eye with EU fisheries ban’, 26 November 2013</p><p>
<a href="http://www.7newsbelize.com/sstory.php?nid=27171" target="_self">http://www.7newsbelize.com/sstory.php?nid=27171</a></p><p><i>Atuna.com</i>, ‘Ghana seeking regional coop to avoid being locked out of EU market’, 29 November 2013</p><p>
<a href="http://www.atuna.com/apps/public/ViewArticle.asp?ID=13709" target="_self">http://www.atuna.com/apps/public/ViewArticle.asp?ID=13709</a></p><p><i>VOA Cambodia</i>, ‘Fisheries officials angered by EU import ban, 30 November 2013</p><p>
<a href="http://www.voacambodia.com/content/fisheries-officials-angered-by-eu-ban/1800472.html" target="_self">http://www.voacambodia.com/content/fisheries-officials-angered-by-eu-ban...</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>The formal procedure to be followed is that the EU Council will endorse the EC proposal to put Guinea, Belize and Cambodia on the list of “non-cooperating countries against IUU fishing”. The import ban on fish products caught by vessels flying the flag of these countries is one sanction taken against such non-cooperating countries, another being that no other fisheries relations (e.g. private licences, fishing agreements) can be maintained by EU operators with them. It will now be up to these three countries to follow the IUU regulation procedure, which requests that they show that shortcomings have been addressed, before ‘de-listing’ can be considered. In the case of Belize, the main issue concerns the way it exerts its responsibilities as a “flag of convenience state” – i.e. being unable to monitor and control vessels flying its flag operating in African waters. The Guinean situation is more complex, as Guinea has issues to solve both as a flag state and as a coastal state – leaving the door open to vessels engaged in illegal operations in its waters. Guinea therefore needs to engage in a reform of its overall fishing policy, for which political will, and financial and human means are necessary.</p>
		</div>
		
